post_text:
Dear NPUSC Family,

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/HPV33LQ

This communication is a follow up survey to inform Return to School planning for this August. The brief survey seeks additional input about your current views on the best Return to School option, views on local county mask ordinances in a school context, and the possibility of an alternative option for NPUSC families not ready to return their students.

This survey will be open July 20th through July 26th at 6 pm CST. Survey results will be published July 27th and will be reviewed as input at the July 27th NPUSC school board meeting. The NPUSC School Board plans to hear public input and make final decisions at this board meeting about our Return to School plan. This meeting will take place July 27th at 6 pm CST at the New Prairie High School

Please contact my office if you have any questions or comments, thank you.

Paul White, PhD

NPUSC Superintendent

Dear NPUSC Family & Staff,

Yesterday the Indiana Department of Education announced that all Indiana school facilities must remain closed through June 30th. As a result, the Graduation Commencement ceremony for our seniors will take place on July 19th, or the weekend of July 19th if COVID-19 guidelines require us to conduct a modified event. A detailed letter with specific information about a July 19th Graduation event will be sent to Senior families for planning purposes in mid to late May.

Also, due to yesterday’s announcement Driver’s Education programming will be cancelled for this summer. Refunds will be mailed in May. The May 4th date for picking up Driver Education forms is also cancelled.

New Prairie will provide follow up communications for any summer programming that occurs either online or in July as information and plans are developed, thank you for your continued support of our students.

Paul White, PhD

New Prairie United Schools Superintendent

Dear NPUSC Family,

E-Learning instruction for all K-12 students will begin tomorrow, Tuesday, March 17th. Assignments will be posted in most cases by 10 am CST. Some high school staff will need more time due to the completion of professional cleaning of our high school facility on Tuesday morning. Remember that E-Learning instruction will be provided to students Tuesday through Thursday throughout the next three weeks. Finally, any families that need to pick up medications need to contact Kathy Zielke, NPUSC Health Services Director, at 574-654-0410 after Noon CST on Tuesday to make arrangements, thank you.

Dr. Paul White

NPUSC Superintendent

post_text:
Last night, a New Prairie Middle School student received a text message from a number the student did not recognize. The text included a direct threat to the safety and security of the middle school.

Midday today, the content of the text began to circulate amongst the students. A school official eventually was made aware of this threat. As a result, the New Prairie United School Corporation (NPUSC) Administration opted to place the middle school on a “lockout”.

The La Porte County Sheriff’s Office is actively investigating the threat. Additional law enforcement personnel, along with LCSO deputies, are present in all the buildings within the NPUSC.

A systemic dismissal at the middle school will occur this afternoon as this threat continues to be investigated. It’s anticipated the dismissal process will be slower than normal as the students are reunited with their parents or board their bus home.

The LaPorte Co Sheriff's Office and NPUSC ask for your patience while the threat is investigated and during today’s dismissal.

post_text:
Dear NPUSC Middle and High School Family,

Due to loss of water pressure and circulation at our water well recently we are placing all water usage from our system at our middle and high school, as a precaution, on a boil order while we have our water tested. This process takes 48 hours. While the testing is occurring NPUSC will be providing bottled water to students and staff throughout the day and clean drinking water options in the cafeteria at lunch time. Again, this is a precaution as our well was down for only one hour before the issue was restored.

This situation was created by a power surge that impacted our power to the well. This was not caused by on-site construction related to the NPUSC renovation projects. This situation does not impact NPUSC Elementary schools, only New Prairie Middle and High School.

Please feel free to contact my office if you have any questions 574-654-7273 or 219-778-2814.

Dr. Paul White
Superintendent, New Prairie Schools

NPUSC will not be having school on Wednesday, January 30th and Thursday, January 31st, due to extreme cold weather. Last night at the school board meeting, the school board discussed that Wednesday, January 30th and Thursday, January 31st would be traditional call offs and no eLearning will take place. Those two days will be made up at the end of the school year.

When NPUSC began eLearning, it was always the intention of the school board that students and staff would not have eLearning more than 3 consecutive days. NPUSC will still have one eLearning day to use if future inclement weather should occur. Please be safe and use caution in the next two days!

For the past several weeks, our Kindergarten through 8th grade students have been engaged in a Kindness project based on the book and movie Wonder by RJ Palacio. Students participated in a variety of activities and lessons centered on the book and the movement it started: “Choose Kind”. Last week we were fortunate enough to host guest speakers from the MyFace organization who spoke with our students about what life is like for someone with a craniofacial disorder like the book's main character.

Special thanks to the La Porte County Public Library and the Healthcare Foundation of La Porte for their partnership in this project!

NP 50th Anniversary Celebration
August 9, 2018 at 3:11 PM ·

**50th Anniversary Dinner Update!**
Thanks to community donations and increased funds for this event, we have decreased the dinner ticket price to $10 per ticket! We want our whole community to be able to come together and celebrate this important milestone. The dinner will take place on Saturday, September 8th, at 5:30pm. Tickets may be purchased at the NP Central Office. Check out our great menu, being provided by all local vendors. The evening will include a video presentation marking 50 years of history and offer live music. All guests will also receive this exclusive mason jar drinking glass to commemorate the event!

**For those that have already purchased tickets, PLEASE contact Ashley Robbins as soon as possible to process your refund (574)654-0266. **

Click on the link below at 1:30 pm central time to view graduation online or follow the instructions below.

Watch Graduation Live Online - Click On the Cougar or the Link Below

https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCI_w1BTsvsmjmbT5zsR9WaA

1) Using a smartphone, tablet, or computer, go to YouTube.com using your favorite browser (chrome-firefox-safari, etc).

2) Type ‘CBM Broadcasting’ into the search bar.

3) CBM Broadcasting should be the first result – the logo is a Cougar face, shown below:

4) On the day of graduation, starting at 1:30pm CST, a video will appear with a red “NOW LIVE” notification will appear. Click on that video and watch graduation.

5) Enjoy Graduation!

post_text: NPUSC has missed two school days this school year due to power outages. These days will be made up on 1/15/18 and 2/19/18. Per the NPUSC School Calendar, the next four school cancellations, should they occur, will be made up the same day as an E-Learning Day. If there is a State of Emergency established within our community, then an eLearning day will not occur. The FAQs are on the NPUSC website. If you have any questions regarding an eLearning day, you may contact your student's teacher, principal, or the corporation office.

post_text:
Our hearts go out to New Prairie volunteer Greg Thompson and his family. Greg was riding his bike on SR 2 Saturday morning and was the victim of a hit and run. Greg was taken by helicopter to a South Bend hospital.

Greg is a New Prairie alumni and was part of the “fearsome foursome” of the 79-80 cross country team. As well as being a long time community member, he has been a cornerstone of the New Prairie Track and Cross Country family as a volunteer for over 25 years. We would like to extend our warmest thoughts and wishes to Greg for a quick recovery. For those who wish to support the Thompson family in this time of need please see the link below.

https://www.gofundme.com/greg-thompsons-medical-fund

shared_text:
New Prairie High School
May 27, 2016 at 9:46 PM ·

New Prairie United School Corporation's Teacher and Employee Recognition Breakfast:

Dr. Paul White gathered all the employees this morning in the high school cafeteria to thank everyone for a successful year and to honor employees for 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30 and 35 years of service as well as honoring those employees who are retiring this year.

We are grateful to all of our employees and for all they do for our kids. From food service, to transportation, technology, secretarial staff, custodial and maintenance, to central office, para professionals, special education and all faculty members and administrators, it truly takes a village and every one of these individuals and groups have had an influence on our kids and are partially responsible for 186 seniors that will walk across the gym floor in 8 more days.

Congratulations to all and thank you for what you do for our kids!

Hey Cougar Nation, This is Our House!

post_text:
Thank you to WSBT 22 TV in South Bend for their coverage of our Facility Needs and coming Forum Meetings. We hope to see a big turnout for our first two Forums 10/19 at the NPHS Library 6 pm CST & 10/20 at Olive Elem 5:30 CST. A few things to clarify from the WSBT TV story:

1. What we are considering proposing to the community will be $10 a month or less in a property tax increase for the average homeowner in our district.

2. The construction cost range we are looking at is 25 million to 36 million, depending on community input.

3. The damaged ceiling in the story is not mold, but a damaged acoustics ceiling in our band/choir area in a practice room. Due to the damage we only use the practice room for storage.

I look forward to working with our school community at our Community Forums to share all of the information
about our possible project.

Paul White
New Prairie United Superintendent
